{"id": "1419083223975198934", "channel_id": "1402941858606219294", "author_id": "1301813973703852035", "author_name": "flarinsidia", "content": "Some explanation on this problem in my opinion, since I was originally working on this, and I didn’t expect this come out to be confusing for native English speakers:\nWhen I got the half-translated Miryam voiceline I noticed BIAV had translated all 吾主，祂 into \"the Lord” or “He”, so I guessed that they didn’t mean to refer Tulu as “The King” if the speaker is a Lemurian. Then I decided to use the Lord in the story for almost all references to Tulu…while only a few talks from the high priest or Miryam mentioned the god connected to Tulu \nso basically all “the Lord/our Lord” is Tulu, including the one the high priest mentioned in your example\nI’m not sure if they originally intend not letting Lemurians call Tulu “the King” in order to make a sense of estrangement… though it turns out to be confusing", "timestamp": "2025-09-20T22:10:05.887000+00:00", "type": 19, "mentions": ["88644018673582080"], "reactions": [{"emoji": "celestepray", "emoji_id": "1397414070100951110", "count": 1}], "reply_to": "1419063717135650950"}
